Fifth Avenue, at the N.W. corner of West 53rd Street, showing St. Thomas's P.E. Church, organized 1826. This edifice, designed by Upjohn, was built in 1870 and contains a chancel adorned by LaFarge and gold reredos by St. Gaudens.

text:
South on West Side, of Fifth Avenue from N.E. corner of 53rd Street.

November 13, 1932

P.L. Sperr.  Photographer.

Fifth Ave., west side, north from West 53rd to 54th Streets. Shown at the N.W. corner of 53rd Street is St. Thomas Protestant Episcopal Church, organized in 1823 when its first church was at Broadway and Houston Street; then a rural suburb. The parish attained a high degree of prosperity under the rectorship of Dr. Francis L. Hawks, but as early as 1843 the need of a location farther up-town began to be felt, and in 1870 the present edifice was opened for worship which was altered in 1911 to appear as shown.

1936.

W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

Fifth Ave., east side, north from 54th Street, as viewed northward from the S.W. corner of 53rd Street. On the left appears a portion of St. Thomas P.E. Church which is on the N.W. corner of 53rd Street. 1936.

Gift of Dr. Michael Wishengrad, A.R.P.S.

West 53rd Street, north side, west of Fifth Ave., showing a clearance where the old building of the Museum of Modern Art stood. Upon this site, and in conjunction with additional space thru the block (former Rockefeller houses) a new Museum will rise. At the extreme right appears the side of St. Thomas Church (P.E.) with its Bridal entrance and the intertwining dollar sign and bridal knot lattice work decoration.

P. L. Sperr.

An eastward view of the same area. Fifth Avenue is at the extreme right. Buildings on the left bear Nos. 23 & 21; the excavation including No's. 19 to 3 inclusive.

Upon this latter clearance will rise a new and larger Museum which will include the Rockefeller properties on 54th Street.
